that 24 hours ago,

340
00:17:57,034 --> 00:17:58,451
I was in an Egyptian tomb.

341
00:17:58,535 --> 00:18:00,369
I didn't know any of you wonderful people,

342
00:18:02,206 --> 00:18:07,168
and here I am now. I'm on the verge
of a madcap Manhattan weekend.

343
00:18:08,921 --> 00:18:11,005
My God, you must really love this picture.

344
00:18:11,715 --> 00:18:13,674
- Me?
- You've been here all day,

345
00:18:13,759 --> 00:18:15,218
and I've seen you here twice before.

346
00:18:15,969 --> 00:18:18,387
- You mean me?
- Yes, you, you. You've...

347
00:18:18,472 --> 00:18:21,015
This is the fifth time you're seeing this.

348
00:18:21,058 --> 00:18:23,601
(WHISPERING) Henry, come here, quickly.

349
00:18:23,685 --> 00:18:25,770
- I gotta speak to you.
- (AUDIENCE EXCLAIMING)

350
00:18:27,022 --> 00:18:28,106
(SCREAMS)

351
00:18:28,190 --> 00:18:30,066
HENRY: Listen, old sport,
you're on the wrong side.

352
00:18:30,150 --> 00:18:31,234
Tom, get back here,

353
00:18:31,318 --> 00:18:32,693
- we're in the middle of a story!
- Leave me alone.

354
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,654
I want to have a look around.
You go on without me.

355
00:18:34,696 --> 00:18:36,405
- HENRY: We can't continue with the story!
- Who are you?

356
00:18:36,490 --> 00:18:37,532
(STAMMERING) Cecilia.

357
00:18:37,616 --> 00:18:39,117
I'll go get the manager!

358
00:18:39,201 --> 00:18:41,160
Let's get out of here
and go somewhere where we can talk.

359
00:18:41,203 --> 00:18:42,829
But you're in the movie!

360
00:18:42,871 --> 00:18:44,789
Wrong, Cecilia, I'm free!

361
00:18:44,873 --> 00:18:48,668
After 2,000 performances
of the same monotonous routine, I'm free!

362
00:18:48,710 --> 00:18:50,837
- HENRY: Call Father Donnelly.
- Tom!

363
00:18:52,631 --> 00:18:54,382
I don't understand. What's going on?

364
00:18:54,466 --> 00:18:55,758
- Who are you?
- Who am I?

365
00:18:55,843 --> 00:18:58,553
You've seen the movie five times.
I'm Tom Baxter.

366
00:18:58,595 --> 00:19:01,222
Poet, adventurer, explorer,
of the Chicago Baxters.

367
00:19:01,265 --> 00:19:02,390
Well, yes, I know you're Tom Baxter.

368
00:19:02,474 --> 00:19:04,350
You wind up with Kitty Haynes,
the nightclub singer,

369
00:19:04,393 --> 00:19:05,893
- but still, I don't...
- Not anymore, I don't have to.

370
00:19:05,978 --> 00:19:08,896
- What do you mean?
- Well, I'm out before the wedding. I'm free.

371
00:19:08,981 --> 00:19:10,189
Don't you have to marry her?

372
00:19:10,232 --> 00:19:11,941
Not while I'm here and she's up there.

373
00:19:12,025 --> 00:19:13,693
Don't you want to? She's so beautiful.

374
00:19:13,735 --> 00:19:15,486
She's not for me. She's too bony.

375
00:19:15,571 --> 00:19:17,655
Kitty Haynes, the nightclub singer, is bony?

376
00:19:17,739 --> 00:19:19,323
I need a place to hide!

377
00:19:19,408 --> 00:19:22,076
Look, I'm never going back,
now that I've met you.

378
00:19:22,161 --> 00:19:25,121
A place to hide? A place to hide?

379
00:19:25,789 --> 00:19:27,582
What's happening? What's going on?

380
00:19:27,666 --> 00:19:29,834
Tom's left. He just walked right out.

381
00:19:29,918 --> 00:19:31,794
I don't know how he did it. I can't get out.

382
00:19:31,879 --> 00:19:32,920
This is just disgusting.

383
00:19:33,005 --> 00:19:35,423
I am an heiress
and I don't have to put up with this!

384
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:36,883
He left the picture?

385
00:19:36,925 --> 00:19:39,010
Oh, my gosh. Well, don't panic.

386
00:19:39,094 --> 00:19:41,179
Just stay up there and keep calm.

387
00:19:41,263 --> 00:19:42,305
Keep calm?

388
00:19:42,389 --> 00:19:43,431
Are you crazy?
What do you mean, "keep calm"?

389
00:19:43,473 --> 00:19:45,141
- Somebody call for a priest?
- Thank God you're here.

390
00:19:45,225 --> 00:19:47,226
- Wait a minute, this is the second reel.
- That's the point.

391
00:19:47,269 --> 00:19:49,145
- I'm not on till later.
- Tom's gone.

392
00:19:49,229 --> 00:19:50,688
Can't you go on? There's an audience.

393
00:19:50,772 --> 00:19:53,065
RITA: How?
Tom was the linchpin of the story.

394
00:19:53,108 --> 00:19:54,567
That's right! Whoever you are, you see, sir,

395
00:19:54,610 --> 00:19:55,651
although this is basically my story,

396
00:19:55,736 --> 00:19:57,653
- Tom moves the exposition along.
- What do you mean, your story?

397
00:19:57,738 --> 00:19:58,738
It's not your story,

398
00:19:58,780 --> 00:20:00,698
it's the story
of a man's quest for self-fulfillment.

399
00:20:00,782 --> 00:20:02,742
- It's the story of a complex, tortured soul.
- Oh, stop that...

400
00:20:02,784 --> 00:20:04,327
It's story of the effect of money
on true romance...

401
00:20:04,411 --> 00:20:05,453
I don't think money comes into it.

402
00:20:05,495 --> 00:20:07,663
...my upbringing, my wealth,
my private schools.

403
00:20:07,748 --> 00:20:09,874
I'm the one who marries royalty.

404
00:20:09,958 --> 00:20:11,250
- I'm the one...
- Nobody cares...

405
00:20:11,293 --> 00:20:12,793
A humble kid...
What do you mean, they don't care?

406
00:20:12,878 --> 00:20:15,171
They wouldn't
sell a ticket if it were your story.

407
00:20:15,255 --> 00:20:17,173
(ALL ARGUING)

408
00:20:17,257 --> 00:20:19,800
- Stop arguing.
- RITA: And do what?

409
00:20:19,927 --> 00:20:21,719
Maybe you should just
turn the projector off.

410
00:20:21,803 --> 00:20:23,763
No! No! Don't turn the projector off!

411
00:20:23,847 --> 00:20:25,681
No! No, it gets black and we disappear.

412
00:20:25,766 --> 00:20:27,642
- Calm down...
- Easy, easy. Easy, easy.

413
00:20:27,726 --> 00:20:29,310
Easy, my son. We're all in this together.

414
00:20:29,394 --> 00:20:32,897
Yes, but you don't
understand what it's like to disappear

415
00:20:32,981 --> 00:20:34,815
and to be nothing, to be annihilated.

416
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:36,859
So don't turn the projector off.

417
00:20:36,944 --> 00:20:38,694
Miss Rita, your bath is ready.

418
00:20:38,820 --> 00:20:40,655
- Not now, dear.
- Well, what's going on?

419
00:20:40,697 --> 00:20:42,031
- Come in and sit down, Delilah.
- Be quiet, Delilah.

420
00:20:42,115 --> 00:20:43,157
Well, what's he doing here?

421
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:45,576
- Have a martini.
- He's not supposed to be here till reel six.

422
00:20:45,661 --> 00:20:47,662
- We know that, Delilah.
- What the hell is going on?

423
00:20:47,704 --> 00:20:48,871
Is somebody trying to hustle me?

424
00:20:48,956 --> 00:20:50,081
They're not trying to hustle you.

425
00:20:52,668 --> 00:20:55,044
TOM: Hey, I know what this is,
it's an amusement park!

426
00:20:55,128 --> 00:20:57,922
CECILIA: Yeah, it's usually pretty dead
around here until summer.

427
00:20:58,006 --> 00:21:00,424
I know exactly what an amusement park is,

428
00:21:00,509 --> 00:21:02,718
- and what goes on. I do!
- Well, good.

429
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:05,137
It's written into my character.

430
00:21:05,180 --> 00:21:06,764
Remember, I invite Kitty to Luna Park,

431
00:21:06,848 --> 00:21:08,391
but she prefers just to stay home and talk?

432
00:21:08,475 --> 00:21:11,018
- Oh, yes.
- So, it's in me!

433
00:21:11,103 --> 00:21:13,521
Oh, too bad nothing's open. I'm starved!

434
00:21:13,563 --> 00:21:14,939
- Oh, you are?
- Well, yeah,

435
00:21:15,023 --> 00:21:17,358
I, uh, left the movie
before the Copacabana scene.

436
00:21:17,442 --> 00:21:19,110
- So that's when I usually eat.
- Oh, wait a minute,

437
00:21:19,194 --> 00:21:21,570
what am I thinking?
Look, here, I've got a whole bag of popcorn.

438
00:21:21,655 --> 00:21:23,489
- You can have that.
- Oh, wow.

439
00:21:23,573 --> 00:21:25,491
Also, I have a Milky Way bar you might...

440
00:21:25,575 --> 00:21:28,160
- No, that's, popcorn is...
- You might want it later.

441
00:21:29,538 --> 00:21:30,579
Boy!

442
00:21:30,706 --> 00:21:32,707
So that's what popcorn tastes like.

443
00:21:32,791 --> 00:21:36,377
I've been watching
people eat it for all those performances.

444
00:21:36,420 --> 00:21:38,671
When they rattle
those bags, though, that's, uh...

445
00:21:38,714 --> 00:21:39,964
- That's not...
...kind of annoying.

446
00:21:40,048 --> 00:21:42,300
I still don't understand what's going on.

447
00:21:42,384 --> 00:21:43,884
I wanted to meet you.

448
00:21:43,927 --> 00:21:45,511
Don't tell me you
didn't see me looking at you

449
00:21:45,554 --> 00:21:47,179
just out of the corner of my eye.

450
00:21:47,222 --> 00:21:48,973
When Kitty Haynes
was doing her nightclub number?

451
00:21:49,057 --> 00:21:51,976
Oh, wait a minute,
I did, I remember seeing you kind of...

452
00:21:52,102 --> 00:21:53,936
You were looking
off to the side, somehow, but...

453
00:21:54,021 --> 00:21:56,272
- Sure.
- I never thought it was to me.

454
00:21:56,356 --> 00:21:58,899
Yeah, when we
take the drive to that little country inn?

455
00:21:58,942 --> 00:22:00,901
When I propose to Kitty?
I was looking at you.

456
00:22:00,986 --> 00:22:03,279
Oh, no, Kitty
looked so beautiful in that black dress.

457
00:22:03,363 --> 00:22:05,573
Oh, no, she's nothing compared to you.

458
00:22:05,615 --> 00:22:08,326
What are you talking about? I'm nothing.

459
00:22:08,410 --> 00:22:10,369
Like hell you are. You are fetching.

460
00:22:10,412 --> 00:22:12,455
- Fetching?
- Fetching.

461
00:22:12,539 --> 00:22:15,041
Dad liked to use that word
about Mom back in Chicago.

462
00:22:15,083 --> 00:22:17,418
"Man!" he'd say, "You're rather fetching."

463
00:22:17,502 --> 00:22:18,711
(GIGGLES)

464
00:22:19,713 --> 00:22:20,755
Dad was a card.

465
00:22:20,839 --> 00:22:23,090
I never met him.
He died before the movie begins.

466
00:22:23,175 --> 00:22:26,635
I have to confess.
My eye did always go to you

467
00:22:26,720 --> 00:22:29,930
- up on the screen. Really.
- Really?

468
00:22:30,682 --> 00:22:33,517
Even when I'm around Detective Sims
and Henry Adams, the playboy.

469
00:22:33,602 --> 00:22:36,103
Yes, even though
you're not the main character,

470
00:22:36,188 --> 00:22:37,646
you're the one you look at.

471
00:22:38,190 --> 00:22:39,982
You don't think I'm the main character.

472
00:22:40,108 --> 00:22:42,943
Oh, I didn't mean it that way. No!

473
00:22:43,028 --> 00:22:45,780
I think you were positively essential.

474
00:22:45,864 --> 00:22:48,282
In fact, every time
I saw the movie I kept thinking,

475
00:22:48,325 --> 00:22:50,284
"Tom Baxter's so handsome."

476
00:22:50,369 --> 00:22:51,369
(CHUCKLING)

477
00:22:56,291 --> 00:22:58,125
Shouldn't you be getting back?

478
00:22:58,168 --> 00:23:01,128
I want to live.
I want to be free to make my own choices.

479
00:23:01,171 --> 00:23:03,798
Right now,
the country's not in such great shape.

480
00:23:04,633 --> 00:23:07,385
- What do you mean?
- Well, we're in the middle of a depression.

481
00:23:07,469 --> 00:23:09,136
Everybody's very poor...

482
00:23:10,389 --> 00:23:12,473
I got plenty, look at this!

483
00:23:13,642 --> 00:23:17,353
But, they need you.
The story doesn't work without you.

484
00:23:17,854 --> 00:23:19,855
Cecilia, I'm in love with you.

485
00:23:20,816 --> 00:23:22,233
I'm married...

486
00:23:22,776 --> 00:23:24,151
Happily?

487
00:23:25,404 --> 00:23:27,738
I really should get back home.
I have to cook dinner.

488
00:23:27,823 --> 00:23:29,490
Just slip away from your husband tonight.

489
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:31,158
Meet me here. I'll wait for you.

490
00:23:31,201 --> 00:23:33,786
I want to learn
about the real world with you.

491
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:35,246
I can't.

492
00:23:35,539 --> 00:23:36,622
Well, look at it this way.

493
00:23:36,665 --> 00:23:39,166
How many times
is a man so taken with a woman

494
00:23:39,209 --> 00:23:41,210
that he walks off the screen to get her?

495
00:23:44,548 --> 00:23:47,091
Okay, okay, let's not panic. We're all adults.

496
00:23:47,175 --> 00:23:48,843
Bored of sitting around.
I'm a dramatic character.

497
00:23:48,885 --> 00:23:50,010
I need forward motion.

498
00:23:50,053 --> 00:23:51,470
Here comes the Countess and Larry.

499
00:23:51,513 --> 00:23:52,763
Where is everybody?

500
00:23:52,848 --> 00:23:54,473
Weren't we meeting at the Copacabana?

501
00:23:54,516 --> 00:23:56,016
- HENRY: Tom's gone.
- What?

502
00:23:56,101 --> 00:23:57,685
- He left the film.
- What?

503
00:23:57,727 --> 00:23:59,270
The bum walked out on us.

504
00:23:59,354 --> 00:24:01,772
(STAMMERING) But the Copa
is where the two of us meet.

505
00:24:01,857 --> 00:24:03,232
I'm trying to get him to marry me.

506
00:24:03,316 --> 00:24:05,901
Forget it. I'm tired
of marrying you every night anyway.

507
00:24:05,986 --> 00:24:07,236
We never even get to the bedroom.

508
00:24:07,362 --> 00:24:09,864
- Where did Tom go?
- Into the real world.

509
00:24:09,948 --> 00:24:12,032
That two-bit minor character
leaves and we're stuck.

510
00:24:12,117 --> 00:24:13,784
I wonder what it's like out there.

511
00:24:13,869 --> 00:24:16,203
They don't look like
they're having too much fun to me.

512
00:24:16,580 --> 00:24:18,497
Hey, what the hell kind of movie is this?

513
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:21,208
WOMAN: The paper said it was a romance,
set all over the world!

514
00:24:21,293 --> 00:24:24,211
Look, don't tell us your sad stories.
You think we like this?

515
00:24:24,254 --> 00:24:28,007
Look at this.
They sit around and talk, and no action?

516
00:24:28,133 --> 00:24:30,050
- Nothing happens?
- I want my money back.

517
00:24:30,093 --> 00:24:32,052
- This is outrageous!
- Shh. Why don't you stop yapping?

518
00:24:32,095 --> 00:24:33,387
We've got problems of our own.

519
00:24:33,430 --> 00:24:34,722
You can't talk to my wife like that.

520
00:24:34,806 --> 00:24:35,931
Who do you think you are?

521
00:24:36,016 --> 00:24:38,184
I'm a genuine Countess with a lot of dough,

522
00:24:38,226 --> 00:24:40,311
and if that's your wife, she's a tub of guts.

523
00:24:40,395 --> 00:24:43,189
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

524
00:24:45,901 --> 00:24:47,276
(GLASS SHATTERS)

525
00:24:48,069 --> 00:24:50,237
Hey, what are you so nervous about?

526
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:52,031
Oh, I'm not.

527
00:24:52,866 --> 00:24:54,241
There's too much pepper in the sauce.

528
00:24:54,284 --> 00:24:56,660
I told you to go easy on the pepper.

529
00:24:57,412 --> 00:24:58,787
Hey, Monk?

530
00:24:59,122 --> 00:25:00,247
Are you, uh...

531
00:25:00,290 --> 00:25:03,792
I guess you and the guys
are probably going out again tonight, huh?

532
00:25:03,919 --> 00:25:06,879
No, I'm not. My back is acting up again.

533
00:25:06,922 --> 00:25:09,298
You gotta give me one
of your special rubdowns. I bought liniment.

534
00:25:09,382 --> 00:25:11,217
- Oh, no.
- What?

535
00:25:12,052 --> 00:25:13,552
Well, I can't.

536
00:25:15,388 --> 00:25:16,639
What do you mean, you can't?

537
00:25:16,765 --> 00:25:18,933
I'm sorry, I didn't mean I can't, I mean,

538
00:25:19,017 --> 00:25:20,601
(STAMMERING) I made some plans, I...

539
00:25:20,727 --> 00:25:22,311
You made plans?

540
00:25:22,437 --> 00:25:25,189
Well, I did. I said I'd...

541
00:25:25,273 --> 00:25:27,608
I'd baby-sit tonight.

542
00:25:27,651 --> 00:25:31,195
I... You know, I ran
into Mrs. Lorenzo and, in the...

543
00:25:31,279 --> 00:25:33,239
I'm saying in the restaurant,
in the street today...

544
00:25:33,281 --> 00:25:35,991
And she has some, you know, I don't know,

545
00:25:36,076 --> 00:25:39,453
I think it was social club meeting or
something she wanted to go to...

546
00:25:40,288 --> 00:25:41,789
Yeah, it won't be too long.

547
00:25:41,873 --> 00:25:44,458
- Yeah, well, I think it's a great idea.
- Yeah?

548
00:25:44,584 --> 00:25:47,336
- Good. Yeah.
- Yeah, because we can use every penny.

549
00:25:47,420 --> 00:25:48,921
All right, so what am I going to do
about my back?

550
00:25:48,964 --> 00:25:51,006
Oh well, don't worry.
You know, I can do some now,

551
00:25:51,091 --> 00:25:52,925
and I'll do some when I come in...

552
00:25:52,968 --> 00:25:55,928
You shouldn't move around too much,
just kind of take it easy.

553
00:25:55,971 --> 00:25:57,972
Well, if you're
gonna go baby-sitting, get paid in cash.

554
00:25:58,056 --> 00:26:00,641
- I will. Okay.
- Don't let her owe you.

555
00:26:02,143 --> 00:26:03,727
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

556
00:26:04,813 --> 00:26:07,231
It's a miracle, a complete miracle!

557
00:26:07,315 --> 00:26:08,857
We want our money back!

558
00:26:08,942 --> 00:26:11,318
I don't pay to watch
those socialites sitting around up there,

559
00:26:11,403 --> 00:26:13,320
and staring back at us,
making nasty remarks.

560
00:26:13,363 --> 00:26:14,738
Is that what they're doing now?

561
00:26:14,823 --> 00:26:16,824
Well, the last time I looked,
the priest had a deck of cards,

562
00:26:16,908 --> 00:26:18,450
and the men were playing pinochle.

563
00:26:18,493 --> 00:26:19,493
How did this first happen?

564
00:26:19,578 --> 00:26:21,954
Well, it's probably all the electrical
storms we had this evening.

565
00:26:21,997 --> 00:26:23,122
The air is charged.

566
00:26:23,206 --> 00:26:24,957
Look, fellas, I depend on the Jewel,

567
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,377
I got personal expenses,
I've got no substitute picture to put in here.

568
00:26:28,461 --> 00:26:30,838
I want my money back! This is a swindle!

569
00:26:30,922 --> 00:26:33,716
There's no story. Mrs. Lupus likes a story.

570
00:26:33,800 --> 00:26:36,635
I still think you should
turn the projector off and shut down.

571
00:26:36,678 --> 00:26:38,345
This could be the work of Reds,
or anarchists.

572
00:26:38,430 --> 00:26:40,306
You can't do that.
If he turns off the projector,

573
00:26:40,348 --> 00:26:44,101
you're liable to strand
this Tom Baxter out in the world someplace.

574
00:26:44,185 --> 00:26:45,686
You want an extra guy running around?

575
00:26:45,812 --> 00:26:48,522
I saw the movie just last week.
This is not what happens!

576
00:26:48,607 --> 00:26:50,357
Where is the Tom Baxter character?

577
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:52,067
You'll get your money back.

578
00:26:52,152 --> 00:26:54,737
I want what happened
in the movie last week to happen this week,

579
00:26:54,821 --> 00:26:57,031
otherwise what's life all about anyway?

580
00:26:57,073 --> 00:26:58,741
Can't we just go in and take a look?

581
00:26:58,825 --> 00:27:00,409
We don't want to stay long.

582
00:27:00,493 --> 00:27:02,745
If you want to see it,
you have to pay admission.

583
00:27:02,829 --> 00:27:04,496
Okay, keep moving, folks!

584
00:27:06,708 --> 00:27:08,375
Any word about Tom Baxter?

585
00:27:08,460 --> 00:27:09,710
Nothing yet.

586
00:27:09,753 --> 00:27:11,378
So what are you people doing here?

587
00:27:11,463 --> 00:27:14,381
We can't continue
the story till Tom gets back.

588
00:27:14,424 --> 00:27:16,300
Oh, we don't mind observing you all.

589
00:27:16,384 --> 00:27:19,219
Yes, my husband
is a student of the human personality.

590
00:27:19,262 --> 00:27:21,513
Oh, yeah? Well, we're not human.

591
00:27:21,556 --> 00:27:23,891
It doesn't matter to Harold.
He has trouble with humans.

592
00:27:23,975 --> 00:27:25,351
I have trouble?

593
00:27:25,393 --> 00:27:27,394
Where do I have trouble
with the real people?

594
00:27:27,437 --> 00:27:29,647
Oh, I suppose you behave
perfectly with Donald?

595
00:27:29,731 --> 00:27:31,357
He won't speak to my own son-in-law.

596
00:27:31,399 --> 00:27:33,442
I won't speak? The kid is quiet.

597
00:27:33,526 --> 00:27:34,610
He never makes conversation.

598
00:27:34,694 --> 00:27:37,905
- He has to be drawn out.
- I don't like to draw people out.

599
00:27:37,947 --> 00:27:41,033
That's what I said.
He has trouble with live humans.

600
00:27:41,534 --> 00:27:43,869
Yes, yes, R.K.O.

601
00:27:44,371 --> 00:27:47,247
I want to speak to Mr. Raoul Hirsch.

602
00:27:48,124 --> 00:27:50,376
Yes, Mr. Hirsch.

603
00:27:50,960 --> 00:27:54,254
He's the producer of
The Purple Rose Of Cairo. Yes.

604
00:27:54,923 --> 00:27:56,423
No, he's not.

605
00:27:56,508 --> 00:27:58,425
Just tell him I have a theater in New Jersey,

606
00:27:58,510 --> 00:28:00,469
and there's a crisis with his film.

607
00:28:01,262 --> 00:28:03,889
Yes, this is Mr. Hirsch. What's the problem?

608
00:28:05,433 --> 00:28:06,433
What?

609
00:28:06,559 --> 00:28:08,894
They're all just
sitting around up there on the screen.

610
00:28:08,937 --> 00:28:12,439
Rita, the Countess,
Larry Wilde, the playboy.

611
00:28:13,358 --> 00:28:15,109
People are demanding their money back.

612
00:28:15,151 --> 00:28:17,569
The theater is nine-tenths empty.

613
00:28:18,154 --> 00:28:19,697
Come on, take a walk, will you?

614
00:28:19,781 --> 00:28:21,949
Look, he just walked out!

615
00:28:22,033 --> 00:28:24,618
Baxter! The Communist is screaming.

616
00:28:24,703 --> 00:28:26,912
The priest in reel five is in reel two!

617
00:28:27,330 --> 00:28:29,248
How can he come off the screen?
It's impossible.

618
00:28:29,290 --> 00:28:30,708
It's never happened before in history.

619
00:28:30,792 --> 00:28:32,126
Just because a thing never happened before

620
00:28:32,168 --> 00:28:33,794
doesn't mean it can't happen for a first time.

621
00:28:33,878 --> 00:28:35,963
That's all you'll need.
Hundreds of Tom Baxters,

622
00:28:36,047 --> 00:28:37,631
on the loose, running around.

623
00:28:37,716 --> 00:28:38,757
Hundreds?

624
00:28:38,800 --> 00:28:41,552
As your lawyer,
I advise you to get control of it fast.

625
00:28:41,636 --> 00:28:43,637
A character from one of your productions
on the loose?

626
00:28:43,722 --> 00:28:45,222
Who knows what he's capable of?

627
00:28:45,306 --> 00:28:48,016
Robbery, murder. I see lawsuits.

628
00:28:48,101 --> 00:28:51,103
I'd charter a plane right away,
and I'd get down there fast.

629
00:28:52,272 --> 00:28:53,564
Get me Gil Shepherd.

630
00:28:54,190 --> 00:28:55,983
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

631
00:28:59,904 --> 00:29:01,822
Sorry, I'm not too light on my feet.

632
00:29:01,865 --> 00:29:03,949
Oh, no, you're a feather in my arms.

633
00:29:03,992 --> 00:29:05,993
Oh, Monk never took me dancing.

634
00:29:06,077 --> 00:29:08,537
I... Not even when we first met.

635
00:29:08,621 --> 00:29:09,913
Not even if I begged him.

636
00:29:09,998 --> 00:29:12,374
Really? So, it's been bad for you.

637
00:29:12,459 --> 00:29:15,502
Oh, it's been hard for everyone.

638
00:29:15,587 --> 00:29:20,257
You know,
living in a world with no jobs and wars.

639
00:29:20,341 --> 00:29:22,676
You, you probably
never even heard of the Great War.

640
00:29:22,761 --> 00:29:24,303
No, I'm sorry. I missed it.

641
00:29:24,345 --> 00:29:28,724
Yeah, well, people get old and sick

642
00:29:28,808 --> 00:29:31,018
and never find true love.

643
00:29:31,352 --> 00:29:33,729
Boy, you know, where I come from,
people, they don't disappoint.

644
00:29:33,813 --> 00:29:36,774
They're consistent. They're always reliable.

645
00:29:37,108 --> 00:29:39,693
You don't find that kind in real life.

646
00:29:40,195 --> 00:29:41,487
You have.

647
00:29:42,197 --> 00:29:44,114
(LOUD MUSIC PLAYING)

648
00:29:46,034 --> 00:29:47,868
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

649
00:29:51,664 --> 00:29:54,875
Is it true they're talking to you
about the life of Lindbergh?

650
00:29:55,043 --> 00:29:57,669
GIL: It's nearly set,
but don't print it till it's firm.

651
00:29:57,712 --> 00:30:00,047
You were great in The Purple Rose of Cairo.

652
00:30:00,131 --> 00:30:01,757
Thanks, I was, uh...

653
00:30:01,883 --> 00:30:04,885
Did you know I was
singled out by all the East Coast critics?

654
00:30:04,928 --> 00:30:07,930
Mmm-hmm.
The New York Times said that I was...

655
00:30:08,056 --> 00:30:12,267
I had almost too smoldering a quality
to just play comedy.

656
00:30:12,352 --> 00:30:15,562
Would you play Lindbergh
the way you played Tom Baxter?

657
00:30:15,647 --> 00:30:16,980
Would I play... No, of course not.

658
00:30:17,065 --> 00:30:18,732
Tom was kind of a change of pace for me.

659
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:20,776
He was from my earlier roles.

660
00:30:20,860 --> 00:30:27,241
I played Tom Baxter with a kind of a
poetic, idealistic quality that, uh...

661
00:30:27,283 --> 00:30:31,245
Just... Lindbergh was a loner.
He was just self-reliant.

662
00:30:32,413 --> 00:30:33,664
I'd have to work
it out with my dialogue coach.

663
00:30:33,748 --> 00:30:35,374
He's a genius. He'll...

664
00:30:35,416 --> 00:30:36,917
Gil, can I see you for a minute?
Alone, please?

665
00:30:37,001 --> 00:30:38,335
- Would you excuse me? I'm sorry.
- Sure.

666
00:30:38,419 --> 00:30:40,128
- Right over here.
- What's up?

667
00:30:40,213 --> 00:30:43,340
Tom Baxter's come down off the screen,
and he's running around New Jersey.

668
00:30:43,424 --> 00:30:45,592
- What are you talking about?
- I just spoke to Raoul Hirsch.

669
00:30:45,677 --> 00:30:47,219
Nobody knows how it happened.
But he's done it.

670
00:30:47,303 --> 00:30:49,388
How could he do that?
It's not physically possible.

671
00:30:49,430 --> 00:30:50,931
In New Jersey anything can happen.

672
00:30:50,974 --> 00:30:52,391
But I created the character.

673
00:30:52,433 --> 00:30:53,851
That's my point.

674
00:30:54,394 --> 00:30:56,520
As your agent, I would hate to see
anything happen to your career,

675
00:30:56,604 --> 00:30:57,896
now that it is starting to move.

676
00:30:57,939 --> 00:30:59,189
- What, like, like, like what?
- Who knows?

677
00:30:59,274 --> 00:31:00,732
There's a double of you on the loose.

678
00:31:00,775 --> 00:31:03,402
What's he up to?
Is he robbing banks? Is he raping broads?

679
00:31:03,444 --> 00:31:05,195
- But, is he?
- Who knows?

680
00:31:06,030 --> 00:31:07,364
Look, the last thing we need

681
00:31:07,448 --> 00:31:09,533
- is for you to get a...
- Shh.

682
00:31:10,368 --> 00:31:12,327
The last thing we need
is for you to get a reputation

683
00:31:12,412 --> 00:31:14,496
- as somehow difficult.
- But I'm not, it's not my fault!

684
00:31:14,581 --> 00:31:18,125
Raoul Hirsch already said,
if you can't control your own creation,

685
00:31:18,167 --> 00:31:19,960
- nobody's going to risk a picture on you.
- Oh, my God!

686
00:31:20,003 --> 00:31:22,045
There goes...
I mean, I worked so hard to make him real.

687
00:31:22,130 --> 00:31:23,547
- Yeah, well, maybe you overdid it.
- Jeez!

688
00:31:23,631 --> 00:31:25,007
- I'll sue my dialogue coach, that louse.
- Look,

689
00:31:25,091 --> 00:31:27,217
you've got to fly down there
and check into this, quick.

690
00:31:27,302 --> 00:31:29,636
Right now, it's only one movie house,
but who knows?

691
00:31:29,679 --> 00:31:31,471
I can't, I'm afraid to fly.

692
00:31:31,556 --> 00:31:34,516
Gil, this is the scandal of all time.

693
00:31:34,601 --> 00:31:37,603
You know what happened
to Fatty Arbuckle's career?

694
00:31:37,645 --> 00:31:39,605
- I'll fly. I'll fly.
- Good.

695
00:31:40,815 --> 00:31:42,983
This is how they drink champagne in Cairo.

696
00:31:44,569 --> 00:31:46,361
I never had champagne before.

697
00:31:46,487 --> 00:31:49,323
- I feel... It makes me feel silly.
- It's supposed to.

698
00:31:49,449 --> 00:31:50,657
(CHUCKLING) Yeah.

699
00:31:50,783 --> 00:31:51,950
The check, as you requested, sir.

700
00:31:51,993 --> 00:31:53,201
Ah.

701
00:31:53,286 --> 00:31:55,287
Ah! It's so much!

702
00:31:55,330 --> 00:31:57,122
- Oh...
- I hope found it to your liking, sir.

703
00:31:57,832 --> 00:31:59,499
- It was superb.
- Oh, it was. It was wonderful.

704
00:31:59,584 --> 00:32:01,710
My compliments to the chef.

705
00:32:01,794 --> 00:32:04,463
And, uh, keep 20% for yourself.

706
00:32:04,547 --> 00:32:07,257
No, make that 30%.

707
00:32:07,342 --> 00:32:08,967
Yes, quite amusing.

708
00:32:09,844 --> 00:32:12,012
- What is?
- The fake money.

709
00:32:12,764 --> 00:32:14,348
Fake money?

710
00:32:14,432 --> 00:32:17,059
Is it, uh, play money, sir, or stage money?

711
00:32:19,062 --> 00:32:22,022
Keep 30% for yourself,
and stop looking so serious.

712
00:32:23,316 --> 00:32:24,858
I'll get the Maitre D'.

713
00:32:25,860 --> 00:32:27,986
Tom, that's not real money.

714
00:32:28,529 --> 00:32:31,490
Well, what do you mean it's not real money?

715
00:32:32,200 --> 00:32:33,367
Oh, my God.

716
00:32:34,410 --> 00:32:36,328
Uh, do you have any money?

717
00:32:36,371 --> 00:32:38,372
No. What are we going to do?

718
00:32:39,082 --> 00:32:40,624
We're going to have to make a run for it.

719
00:32:40,708 --> 00:32:43,877
No, I can't run.
My ankles are bad from waitressing.

720
00:32:44,212 --> 00:32:46,046
Just get up. Follow me.

